This paper presents an approach to extend the autonomy of exploration robots by enabling them to model and reason about scientific knowledge on-board. The paper focuses on the application of this approach to a Mars exploration mission, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The approach involves the use of Bayesian networks and Monte Carlo Tree Search techniques, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computer vision (cs.CV) research. The paper also discusses the robustness of the approach to uncertainty, which is a common concern in systems and control (cs.SY) research. Finally, the paper presents simulation results and experimental validation, which are common in software engineering (cs.SE) research.
